            "Do the same to both sides",
            "Balance both sides"
          ],
          "hint": "Think about how you maintain the balance of the equation.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the name of the mathematical process used to rearrange a formula to make a different letter the subject?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Transposition",
            "Transpose",
            "Formula rearrangement"
          ],
          "hint": "It starts with 'T'.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "If a value is a multiplier on one side of an equation, what operation must it perform when moved to the other side?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Division",
            "Divide",
            "Dividing"
          ],
          "hint": "You must use the opposite operation.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "How does the 'Golden Rule' of transposition ensure that the relationship between variables in a formula like V = I x R remains mathematically valid after it is rearranged?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Maintains the mathematical balance of the equation",
        "Preserves the equality between both sides",
        "Ensures the ratio between values remains consistent",
        "Prevents changing the actual value of the expression"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP1",
        "TP2"
      ],
      "hint": "Consider what would happen to the 'equals' sign if you only changed one side of the formula."
    },
    {
      "title": "Triangles and Trigonometry",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "Which mathematical theorem is used to calculate the length of the longest side in a right-angled triangle?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Pythagoras’ Theorem",
            "Pythagoras",
            "a squared plus b squared equals c squared"
          ],
          "hint": "It is named after an ancient Greek mathematician.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the technical name for the longest side of a right-angled triangle, located opposite the right angle?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Hypotenuse",
            "The hypotenuse"
          ],
          "hint": "It is the side 'c' in Pythagoras' theorem.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which mnemonic is used to remember the three main trigonometric ratios: Sine, Cosine, and Tangent?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "SOH CAH TOA",
            "SOHCAHTOA"
          ],
          "hint": "It uses the first letters of Sine, Opposite, Hypotenuse, etc.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "In the context of AC electrical theory, why is a right-angled triangle used to represent values like impedance rather than a simple linear addition?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Represents vector addition of different properties",
        "Accounts for the phase angle between values",
        "Combines different types of opposition that are not in phase",
        "Allows for the calculation of the total magnitude using Pythagoras"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP1",
        "TP2"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about how AC values don't always act in the same direction at the same time."
    },
    {
      "title": "Statistics in Electrical Work",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "Which statistical term refers to the mathematical average found by adding a set of values together and dividing by the count?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Mean",
            "The mean",
            "Arithmetic mean"
          ],
          "hint": "It is the most common type of average used for test results.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the primary purpose of using basic statistics when reviewing a set of Earth Loop Impedance test results?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Analyzing data",
            "Identifying patterns",
            "Finding averages",
            "Interpreting test results"
          ],
          "hint": "Consider why we look at multiple results together rather than just one.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1",
            "TP2"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which statistical value represents the middle number in a sorted list of data?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Median",
            "The median"
          ],
          "hint": "It is the central value of a data set.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why might an electrician need to calculate the 'mean' of several test results rather than relying on a single individual reading?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Ensures the reliability of the data set",
        "Helps identify and account for outliers or anomalies",
        "Provides a more accurate representation of the installation's state",
        "Reduces the impact of minor measurement fluctuations"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP1",
        "TP2"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about how one single reading might be affected by a temporary loose connection or meter error."
    }
  ]
}

